[This is the Japanese encephalitis virus (JEV) transmission season in northeastern India. However, the above report does not indicate whether these cases are laboratory confirmed as JEV infections or are due to some other etiologic agent.

As mentioned in previous comments, the encephalitis picture in this region of India is complicated, and reports are often confusing. In the previous report of encephalitis in West Bengal, 6 patients have acute encephalitis, while 3 were diagnosed as JE. The above report attributes 14 deaths to JEV infections. The JE virus etiology of some previously reported encephalitis cases has been confirmed by laboratory tests. However, many cases go undiagnosed, or JE virus infection is ruled out, and other etiologies, including Reye syndrome-like disease and lychee consumption, have been proposed. No mention is made of the JE virus vaccination status of the cases above or of the population in the affected area. Vaccination is more likely to be effective for prevention of JE cases than vector control, particularly in the areas of paddy rice cultivation that provide abundant _Culex_ vector mosquito breeding sites. The virus doubtless is endemic in northeastern India. Ardeid birds (heron family) are reservoir hosts.

Maps of India can be seen at http://www.mapsofindia.com/images2/india-map.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3513485,306, West Bengal state at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3513485,323, and Assam state at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3513485,299. - Mod.TY]
